---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
import '../../styles/course.css';
import LessonPage from '../../components/course/LessonPage';
import GatePanel from '../../components/assessment/GatePanel';
---

<BaseLayout title="Dot Product as Weighted Comparison">
  <LessonPage lessonId="L07" client:load>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Question</div>
      <div class="lesson-question">What does a dot product mean?</div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Intuition</div>
      <p>
        The dot product takes two vectors of the same length and produces a single number.
        It multiplies corresponding elements and adds them up.
      </p>
      <p>
        The result tells you something about how similar or aligned the two vectors are.
        If both vectors have large positive values in the same positions, the dot product is large and positive.
        If they point in opposite directions, it is negative.
      </p>
      <p>
        In LLMs, the dot product is everywhere. Attention scores are dot products between query and key vectors.
        Projections are collections of dot products. Understanding this operation is essential.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Toy Example</div>
      <div class="toy-example">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
          Dot product of a = [2, 3, -1] and b = [4, -1, 2]:
        </p>
        <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm);">
          <div style="display: flex; gap: var(--space-4); align-items: center; flex-wrap: wrap;">
            <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; align-items: center;">
              <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost); font-size: var(--text-xs);">multiply</span>
              <div style="display: flex; gap: 12px; margin-top: 4px;">
                <span style="color: var(--sem-token);">2&times;4=<strong>8</strong></span>
                <span style="color: var(--sem-attention);">3&times;(-1)=<strong>-3</strong></span>
                <span style="color: var(--sem-ffn);">(-1)&times;2=<strong>-2</strong></span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">→</span>
            <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; align-items: center;">
              <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost); font-size: var(--text-xs);">sum</span>
              <span style="color: var(--ink-primary); font-size: var(--text-lg); font-weight: 600; margin-top: 4px;">8 + (-3) + (-2) = 3</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-3);">
          Result: <strong>3</strong>. A positive number — the vectors are somewhat aligned.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Shapes</div>
      <div class="shape-card">
        <div>a: [d] &nbsp;&nbsp; b: [d] &nbsp;&nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">(same dimension required)</span></div>
        <div style="color: var(--sem-token); margin-top: var(--space-2);">a &middot; b: scalar &nbsp;&nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">(two vectors in, one number out)</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Math</div>
      <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm); background: var(--surface-3); padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); border-radius: var(--radius-sm); margin: var(--space-3) 0;">
        <div style="color: var(--sem-token);">a &middot; b = &sum;&#x1D62; a&#x1D62; &times; b&#x1D62;</div>
      </div>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
        Multiply each pair, sum the results. Both vectors must have the same dimension.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Implementation Hook</div>
      <div class="impl-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          The dot product is the primitive behind matrix multiplication. In <code>llama.cpp</code>, attention scores are computed as dot products between query and key vectors. The <code>ggml_mul_mat</code> operation performs many dot products at once.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Performance Hook</div>
      <div class="perf-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          A dot product of dimension <em>d</em> requires <em>d</em> multiplications and <em>d-1</em> additions.
          In attention, every token pair requires a dot product. This is why attention cost grows with both sequence length and model dimension.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Check Yourself</div>
      <GatePanel
        client:load
        lessonId="L07"
        gateStrength="soft"
        questions={[
          {
            id: 'L07-q1',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'What is the dot product of [1, 0, 3] and [2, 5, -1]?',
            tag: 'math',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: '-1', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'b', text: '5', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'c', text: '10', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: '(1×2) + (0×5) + (3×(-1)) = 2 + 0 + (-3) = -1',
          },
          {
            id: 'L07-q2',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'Why does the dot product appear in attention?',
            tag: 'conceptual',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'Because it measures how similar two vectors are', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'b', text: 'Because it is the fastest operation on GPUs', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'c', text: 'Because it was invented for transformers', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'Attention uses dot products to compute how much one token should attend to another. Higher dot product = more similar = more attention.',
          },
        ]}
      />
    </div>

  </LessonPage>
</BaseLayout>
